  "prompt": "What does the GDP per capita represent?",
  "response": "The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) per capita is an economic metric that represents the average economic output per person in a specific region, such as a country. It is calculated by dividing the total GDP of the region by its population. Essentially, GDP per capita provides an indication of the average economic productivity and standard of living of the people in that region. It is often used as a measure to compare the economic performance and living conditions between different countries or regions.\n\nFor example, if a country has a GDP of $500 billion and a population of 50 million, the GDP per capita would be $10,000. This means that, on average, each person in that country contributes $10,000 to the economy in terms of economic output. Higher GDP per capita generally suggests a higher standard of living and economic prosperity, although it does not account for income distribution or inequality within the region.",
